    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Munnozia lyrata improperly are experience nausea, cause diarrhea, induce vomiting, and develop skin irritation due to its toxic glycosides, particularly the sesquiterpene lactones, which have been shown to have irritant and emetic properties, leading to gastrointestinal disturbances and dermatological reactions. This is because the sesquiterpene lactones in Munnozia lyrata can cause damage to the epithelial lining of the gastrointestinal tract, leading to nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea. Furthermore, the toxic compounds in Munnozia lyrata can also cause skin irritation, including redness, itching, and blistering, due to its contact dermatitis-inducing properties. The improper use of Munnozia lyrata can also lead to the induction of nausea, which is a common symptom of poisoning by toxic plants. The exact mechanism of the toxic effects of Munnozia lyrata is not fully understood, but it is believed to be related to the disruption of cellular membranes and the interference with cellular metabolism.",
    "uses": "Munnozia lyrata is a plant species used in traditional medicine in various parts of South America, particularly in the Andean region. Its leaves and stems are said to have antiseptic and anti-inflammatory properties, making it useful for treating wounds and skin conditions. The plant is also used to treat fever, digestive issues, and respiratory problems. In some cultures, Munnozia lyrata is believed to have antiviral and antibacterial properties, which can help fight off infections. Additionally, it is sometimes used as a natural remedy for headaches and other minor health issues.",
    "taxonomy": "Munnozia lyrata is classified as a species of flowering plant in the family Asteraceae. This plant belongs to the genus Munnozia, which is a group of plants native to South America. The genus Munnozia is further classified under the subfamily Mutisioideae. The subfamily Mutisioideae is a part of the larger family Asteraceae, which includes a wide range of flowering plants. This classification is based on the plant's morphology and genetic characteristics.",
    "benefits": "Munnozia lyrata is known for its potential medicinal properties, particularly in traditional medicine. Its extracts have been studied for their antioxidant and anti-inflammatory activities. Research suggests that Munnozia lyrata may have hepatoprotective properties, helping to protect the liver from damage. Additionally, it has been found to have antimicrobial properties, which could aid in the treatment of certain infections. Further studies are needed to fully understand the health benefits of Munnozia lyrata and its potential applications.",
    "parts": "Munnozia lyrata has traditionally been used in herbal medicine, with the flowers and leaves being considered the medicinal parts. The plant is believed to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. The flowers and leaves are often used to treat various health issues, including fever, respiratory problems, and digestive issues. The plant's medicinal properties are thought to be due to the presence of bioactive compounds such as flavonoids and phenolic acids. Further research is needed to confirm the efficacy of Munnozia lyrata as a medicinal plant.",
    "intro": "Munnozia lyrata, also known as Lyrata, is a flowering plant species native to the Andean region of South America. The plant has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, with health benefits including anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant effects, which may help to alleviate symptoms of conditions such as arthritis and infections. The bioactive constituents of Munnozia lyrata include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which contribute to its medicinal properties. The most common herbal preparations made with Munnozia lyrata are teas, infusions, and tinctures, often used to support immune function and reduce inflammation."
